VP.SURYA RAOThe boys are young but show amazing talent on the tablas. V. Suryaprakash and V. Vidyasagar hail from a reputed family of tablists. Their father Amrit Kumar is a lecturer of tabla at the G.V.R. Government College of Music and Akashvani and a well-known tabla player.The event was part of Swarajhari's monthly programme and took place at Sri Sivaramakrishna Kshetram, Vijayawada. The boys enthralled the packed crowds with fine rhythmic patterns inteen taland played a number ofmukdasinvilambitanddrittempos. Some intricate patterns were marked with great clarity. Hindustani vocalist and principal of the Music College Ch. Sriramachandra Murthy showered well-deserved praise on the young brothers.The tabla delight was followed by a fine vocal concert by C.V.P. Sastry who was trained in music by his mother Suseela Gopalam, a veenavidushiand Modumudi Sudhakar, vocalvidwan. Sastry's voice was in fine condition and his concert began withSriraga varnamfollowed by the Annamacharya keertana in ReguptiPurushothamudaveevu. The keertana carried admirablekalpana swaras.Next cameNeeke Teliyakapotheof Thyagaraja inAnandabhairavi. After renderingGaruda GamanainNagaswaravali,Marivere Dikkevarayya Ramaof Patnam inShanmukhapriyaand Swati Tirunal'sDeva DevainMayamalavagowlawith remarkablemanodharmam, Sastry presented a finepallaviinKambhojiset toKhandatriputa talamand executed it with precision and confidence. Palaparthi Nageswara Rao on violin and K. Sai Giridhar on the mridangam ably supported him respectively. Sastry's concert came to a close with aTarangamof Narayana TeerthaMadhava Mamava DevainNeelambari.Bottom Template Starts
